## Open Questions

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Q1: Supabase Plan Tier**
> Does the production Supabase instance support the `service_role` key for the local agent? The agent needs to read `biometric_devices` (including encrypted passwords) and write to `agent_command_queue`. If RLS is strict, we may need specific policies.

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> **Q2: Agent Distribution Method**
> Should we package the agent as:
> - A) A standalone `.exe` using `pkg` (zero Node.js dependency for campus IT)
> - B) A Docker container (for campuses with Docker infrastructure)
> - C) A plain Node.js script with install instructions (simplest for us to maintain)
>
> Recommendation: Start with **A** (.exe) for maximum ease of deployment.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Q3: Admin UI for Agent Management**
> Should we add a section in the Admin → Academic Setup → Biometric Structure tab to:
> - Show agent status (online/offline, last heartbeat)
> - Generate the agent secret
> - Download the agent installer
>
> Or should this be Phase 2 (after the core agent works)?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Q4: Webhook Configuration in Production**
> Currently, `configureDeviceWebhook` tells the device to push scans to the cloud URL (`tektoncampus.com/api/biometric/scan`). This requires the campus network to allow the device to reach the internet on port 443.
> 
> Alternative: The agent could also act as a **local webhook receiver** — the device pushes scans to the agent (on the LAN), and the agent forwards them to the cloud. This adds complexity but removes the requirement for devices to have internet access.
>
> Recommendation: Start with the current approach (device pushes directly to cloud). Only build the agent-as-webhook-relay if campus firewalls block outbound device traffic.
